                 <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#0047AB] mb-4">3. Platform Feature Analysis</h2>
                <ul class="space-y-4 text-slate-700">
                    <li><strong class="text-[#0047AB]">Notion:</strong> Your assessment is correct. Upgrading to the Business Plan is the right move. It provides the necessary collaboration features and API access for integrations, serving as the central "operating system" for project management and knowledge. Its calendar sync requires a third-party tool like 2sync for true two-way updates with dependencies, a minor trade-off for its immense flexibility.</li>
                    <li><strong class="text-[#0047AB]">Folk CRM:</strong> I agree with your choice over HubSpot. Folk's native integrations with LinkedIn (via folkX extension) and its WhatsApp CRM capabilities are modern and perfectly suited for your multi-channel outreach. Its UI is clean, intuitive, and the Kanban view for recruiting pipelines meets your exact needs.</li>
                     <li><strong class="text-[#0047AB]">Kanbanchi:</strong> Disagree. While its integration with Google Workspace is deep, its calendar sync is only <strong class="text-red-600">one-way</strong>. Changes in Google Calendar do not reflect back in Kanbanchi, which fails your critical two-way sync and dependency requirement. Notion with an integration partner is a better solution.</li>
                </ul>
